			"id": "6a05ba36-a9b1-4c15-80b5-b531e4e51660",
			"description": "This collection is intended to be used by SP-API developers who want to onboard to [Reports section](https://developer-docs.amazon.com/sp-api/docs/reports-api-v2021-06-30-reference) and/or retrieve **Vendor Retail Analytics and Brand Analytics report types** to analyze their business.\n\nFor detailed information on these reports refer [Vendor Analytics Reports](https://developer-docs.amazon.com/sp-api/docs/report-type-values-analytics) also refer to [Reports API v2021-06-30 Use Case Guide](https://developer-docs.amazon.com/sp-api/docs/reports-api-v2021-06-30-use-case-guide) to learn more on how Reports API work.\n\n## Steps to Follow\n\n- You need the [Brand Analytics role](https://developer-docs.amazon.com/sp-api/docs/roles-in-the-selling-partner-api#role-definitions) approved in your Developer Profile and applied it to your application.\n    \n- Collection Variables tab has all the required variables for the API operations. Modify them with your actual values.\n    \n\n1. Open **Authorization to get Access Token** folder and execute request **GetAccessToken** to get an **access token** in exchange to the refresh token. This access token is passed as a header to all the SP API calls. The access token is automatically stored in the collection's variables.\n    \n2. Open **Create Report Operations folder** where you will find createReport POST requests for the **Vendor Analytics reports**. Submit the request for the desired report types. The resulting `reportId` is automatically stored in the collection's variables.\n    \n3. Execute request **getReport** to check the report processing status, and wait until `Status = DONE`. The resulting `reportDocumentId` is automatically stored in the collection's variables.\n    \n4. Execute request **getReportDocument** to retrieve the report document url. Use the `url` value from the response to get the document data."
		}
